{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/beware-of-using-the-str-casefold-method-when-dealing-with-strings-in-python-bd7b7ccd59ea", "time": 1683008115.035411, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/beware-of-using-the-str-casefold-method-when-dealing-with-strings-in-python-bd7b7ccd59ea/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "Beware of Using the Casefold() Method when Dealing with Strings in Python | by Christos Zeglis | Towards Data Science", "h1": "Beware of Using the Casefold() Method when Dealing with Strings in Python", "description": "Although string handling in Python seems quite easy and fun, attention should be paid to the right use of certain methods; str.casefold() is one of them, and the one this article is mostly about."}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://www.linkedin.com/in/christoszeglis/", "anchor_text": "here", "paragraph_index": 10}], "all_paragraphs": ["The main cause for this article was a bug I spotted on the Instagram app. Specifically, while I was typing a few words I wanted to share with my friends via Instagram Stories, I realized that the string handling was not optimal, at least in Greek, my native language.", "The bug takes place when you change the font types i.e. Neon, Typewriter, Strong, Classic, Modern. So, when you choose the Modern font, you get uppercase letters, and then when you change to the next one, Neon, you get lowercase letters. And this is where the bug appears to exist. The transition to the lowercase letters leads to words that, in specific cases, are misspelled.", "In the Greek language, the equivalent of the English letter \u2018S\u2019 is the letter \u2018Sigma\u2019, which many of you have most probably come across in mathematics. In uppercase it is spelled \u2018\u03a3\u2019, while in lowercase it has two different forms: \u2018\u03c3\u2019 in every case, unless it is positioned at the end of a word, which in that case takes the form \u2018\u03c2\u2019. For example, the word \u2018stable\u2019 translates to \u2018\u03c3\u03c4\u03b1\u03b8\u03b5\u03c1\u03cc\u03c2\u2019. You can see both sigmas appear in this word.", "Now, if you type \u2018\u03a3\u03c4\u03b1\u03b8\u03b5\u03c1\u03cc\u03c2\u2019 on the Instagram Stories text editor, and then try the different font types, you will see the word has turned into \u2018\u03a3\u03c4\u03b1\u03b8\u03b5\u03c1\u03cc\u03c3\u2019, which is incorrect. The final \u2018\u03c2\u2019 has turned into normal \u2018\u03c3\u2019.", "One possible explanation behind this issue, assuming the editor is written in python, could be the wrong use of the string methods:", "Bellow you can see the exact order of command lines that get you to this incorrect result. You can also see what each of these methods does.", "Instead, the correct order of command lines should be the following.", "To demystify each method all you need to see is the official documentation.", "I would suggest using str.casefold() only for caseless comparisons and nowhere else, since you could get into false results territory without even noticing.", "That\u2019s it for today. Hope you found it useful. Till next time!", "You can always find me on LinkedIn by clicking here.", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes."], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2Fbd7b7ccd59ea&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fbeware-of-using-the-str-casefold-method-when-dealing-with-strings-in-python-bd7b7ccd59ea&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=login&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fbeware-of-using-the-str-casefold-method-when-dealing-with